# Migration safety

## Rule
All migrations are backward-compatible within a single release. Every migration ships with:
1. A rollout plan (old version keeps running during the transition).
2. A rollback plan (how to revert if the rollout fails).
3. Tenant backfill strategy if the migration touches per-tenant data.
4. Index impact analysis if the migration adds or drops an index.

## Why
Per-tenant Mongo DBs in fb-rates-go / fb-iqs mean one migration fan-out touches N tenants. MySQL master-data migrations in admin-backend can lock tables used by multiple services. Datastore kind evolution affects in-flight Cloud Run Jobs. Breakage in any of these produces cross-service outages.

## Constraints
- Add fields as optional with defaults first; flip consumers to read them; then make them required in a follow-up release.
- Never drop a column / field / index in the same release that stops writing to it; one-release gap minimum.
- Per-tenant Mongo migrations enumerate `tenant_connection` and run against each tenant DB in a resumable loop.
- MySQL migrations prefer `ALTER TABLE ... ALGORITHM=INPLACE` or an online schema-change tool; table-locking migrations require maintenance windowing.
- Datastore kind additions ship with an `index.yaml` change if indexed queries change.

## Examples

### Good
> Migration `2026-04-21_add_frlc_category`: adds nullable `frlcCategory`; service reads it with `omitempty`; a follow-up migration next release fills backfill and flips it to required.

### Bad
> Migration renames a field in-place and deploys the consumer that expects the new name in the same release.

